{"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"LINK","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automaton","rel":"noopener","target":"blank"}},"1":{"type":"LINK","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"href":"/posts/cellular-automaton/","rel":"","target":"_self"}},"2":{"type":"LINK","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"href":"https://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=2%5E(2%5E9)","rel":"noopener","target":"blank"}}},"blocks":[{"key":"2d01","text":"An automaton (plural: automata or automatons) is a self-operating machine, or a machine or control mechanism designed to automatically follow a predetermined sequence of operations, or respond to predetermined instructions.","type":"blockquote","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"offset":200,"length":13,"key":0}],"data":{}},{"key":"2d02","text":"To get a basic introduction to cellular automata, you should check out my first page about Elementary Cellular Automaton.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"offset":88,"length":30,"key":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"2d03","text":"This next iteration is in 2 dimensions. Time is on the Z axis, so you won't get to look back; the present world is all you can see. In this version of cellular automata, the future world is derived from the parent neighbors of the cell in question. Below you'll see 4 simple ways to count neighbors.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2d04","text":"Below I'm using 4 neighbors. With 4 neighbors, there are 65,535 rules. If I used 9 neighbors, there would be 13,407,807,929,942,597,099,574,024,998,205,846,127,479,365,820,592,393,377,723,561,443,721,764,030,073,546,976,801,874,298,166,903,427,690,031,858,186,486,050,853,753,882,811,946,569,946,433,649,006,084,096 rules. Or 13.4 Quinquagintillion. Math reference: Wolfram Alpha","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"offset":363,"length":13,"key":2}],"data":{}},{"key":"2d05","text":"I have found that rules converted to binary numbers ending in 10110 make for very cool patterns. The arrows will jump you to the next rule that when converted to binary ends in 10110.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}]}
